A form of non-sexual fetishization, where an object, a habit, or a pet takes the place of a loved one. text: I love the no-nonsense straight up, unapologetic, bad ass action of this series and Keanu is perfect for this role. I am worried though about the direction it is heading and a little in 2 but with Halle Berry, I'm worried that is too much drama star power. Laurence Fishburne is a good middle ground but Halle Berry is poorly cast here. Just look back at Catwoman, a bad action movie, and then look at what she is good at, stuff like Monster's Ball or that movie with Benicio Del Toro where her house burned down. Too many stars from the serious drama world are latching on like leeches here and will suck the good right out of this. Just let this be what it was always supposed to be, a fun and bad ass action movie solely focused on John Wick and his amazing story and abilities. I don't need star power or drama, thank you.

text: John Wick has really been a masterful action series so far. Most action films try to present their protagonists as the underdogs, they think this will make the main character more likeable and make the film more believable. Though this causes villains in those films much cooler than the protagonists and the endings where the hero finds a way to stop the villain just feels cliche. John Wick just do opposite of this, they've made it completely obvious from the beginning that Wick is stronger than everyone else and even when he's facing against an army of assassins, it just makes the odds even like Winston says in the first trailer. There are two villains in this trailer, one of them is ridiculed for trying to face John Wick and the other is just complimenting him. While the action movie trailers almost exclusively portray their villains as unbeatable.   John Wick's approach just makes the film a lot more enjoyable to watch. It's more fun to watch and cheer for the hunter, rather than the hunted when it comes to action movies. The best of them always have overpowered protagonists such as series like Bourne, Die Hard, Terminator, The Dark Knight(not as a serie) and Kill Bill.

text: You know what makes this series so great is firstly keanu reeeves is a real practioneer if martial arts, this kind of choreography cant be acquired without long term physical training. Secondly, they made his characters background very realistic. For example if you guys ever watched the first two movies, if you pay attention you will notice that john wick isnt superhuman, he cant do everything. He severely lacks in hand 2 hand combat and whenever he loses access to his gun, he ends up getting handled or tossed over a rail until he best them and finishes them execution style with a weapon. He is a pure gunslinger, so pure that its fluid and unconventional, he either out guns you with skill from a distance or if it is close quarters, he will use judo throws to make u vulnerable and then finish you with a headshot. They made his char very realistic and im glad for that, no one wants to see a superman.

text: Wow.... The John Wick writers and producers are so out of ideas for the 3rd film that they bring Morpheus in, and have Keanu spout his most famous Matrix line "Guns, lots of guns"?  So basically John Wick is trying to pander to Matrix fans in hopes of getting more people to give the John Wick movies a chance.   But the Matrix movies are written with storylines that are Supposed to be deep and filled with backstory, archetype characters, and allegorical complexity. The Matrix films have a whole supporting mythos.  While in almost total opposition,  the John Wick films have very little story, or character development, or any meaning deeper than is needed to move from one action set up to the next. The whole first film's story can be summarized in a single sentence; someone kills a retired hitman's dog, so he returns to the underground world of contract killers in order to kill anyone and anything in his way until he can get his revenge on the dog killer.  With The Matrix, people have filled message boards, blogs, and podcasts with millions of words to explain the story.... And they'd probably Still be talking about it if the second film wasn't much worse, and the third film much worse than the second.  John Wick is fun (at least the first film) because it Isn't deep. There is no thinking required to enjoy John Wick. It is a purely visceral orgy of sight and sound. Violent action for its own sake, done in a fairly fresh style, with great music.  So why the F**k are they doing Matrix homages in John Wick.  Is it perhaps that out of his entire career this is only the second time Keanu has found a character popular enough to actually Warrant the making of sequels?  So they're celebrating that by calling back to the First character he played that lasted more than a single film, And made a decent profit?  I think that may be it. Because Keanu is a very Limited actor. In The Matrix we overlooked the fact that there was no way in hell the way he played Neo fit the fact that he was supposed to be a great hacker.   Seemingly as slow witted as his speech, we just went along with it because the first movie was a breath of fresh air, and a veritable Geek Celebration on celluloid.  In John Wick, he's the strong silent type. There isn't much story or dialogue, just a lot of action... Which is Perfect for Keanu.  I mean.... We all remember when he was cast as a period, British journalist, right?   He's only got One way of speaking, one speed, and very limited emotional range vocally. But he'll work his Ass off learning fighting techniques and stunts, and get strapped into a wire rig and do his own stunts, even while injured.  Keanu once again is in the type of 2 dimensional character and story his acting is best suited for. And he's just awesome at selling action scenes.  But there was no reason to mix The Matrix into John Wick.... Unless this is his final film? That's the only way putting Matrix into John Wick makes sense..... Unless..... John Wick is actually a side story in the Matrix universe. The movie marketing art looks similar.... and some of the lighting and action are very Matrix-like.... So maybe Neo lost his memory, or got put back into a Different Matrix program that allows him greater wish fulfillment. John Wick is actually Neo trapped in the Matrix again.... But this time Morpheus is still asleep as well. üôÑ

text: Still better than 90% of today's action movies but for a John Wick movie it felt quite weak compared to the first two. It might just be because John doesn't have much of an objective beyond surviving. He was out in the open a lot so I kept wondering how he wasn't getting hit. The best action sequences were at the beginning with the library fight and the knife fight which made the rest of the film feel a little underwhelming. The dog fight felt much less John Wick and more like something out of a Pierce Brosnan Bond flick. All out in the open while a dozen guys shoot at the hero but never hit him. It even had Halle Berry. The continental fight was good but again there was a lot of John being out in the open and not getting hit. then there was the fact that the Asian guys were toying with John for some reason. They could've killed him like five times. If there trying to kill him and they know his reputation then you know you shouldn't toy with him.. Then there was the ending where 9 times out of 10 John would've died and in the 1 that he doesn't he should be spending John Wick 4 in a wheelchair and full body cast.

There were a few good kills from the beginning of the film, and scattered throughout, and they need to change things up a bit. The second movie had a much better photography and atmosphere, and you could digest and enjoy the violence more, and also in this one, there are a lot of places where you could see stuntmen waiting to get punched or waiting to attack. All in all, the movie is decent, but for the 4th one, they should fix some of the glaring issues and make it pop even more.

text: So ... if you're looking for a lot of good fight scenes, this movie has it.  If you're watching ANY John Wick movie for anything but good fight scenes (and lots of headshots), then you're in the wrong place.  Although I will say the 10 minutes of Halle Berry and Keanu working together (with her dogs) was awesome ... some of the best fight scene choreography I've seen in a while.  Even the dogs were spot on.  Plot 2/5.  Story 1/5.  Acting 3/5.  Action 4.5/5.  Someone needs to parody these action movies and soon.  And the parody needs to include characters that resemble, John Wick, Jason Bourne and Bryan Mills (Liam Neeson in Taken).  That may very well be a parody that could rival an original with box office ticket sales.   Thanks Keanu.  Keep em coming.  And bring Halle back in John Wick 4.  She looks good in that role.

text: John Wick 1 and 2 are brilliant. John Wick 3 is full of plot holes, it's like an early CGI film with nonsense story, but replace CGI with fight scenes. He rides a horse and the motorcyclists ride next to him to get shot, instead of shooting him in the back.That was when the problems started.  Wick avenged a killed a member of the council in Wick 2, so the council would not care, but THAT fact is IGNORED the entire film. Resurrecting characters/dogs, Halle Berry has 2 dogs, 1 Dog dies, then 2 Dogs go out killing everyone. Steals John Wicks motivation, 'you killed my dog'. A manager, who is also an assassin as good as Wick? Fake female empowerment. Minimizes/Mocks Wick/Baba Yaga as a character. Pigeon King Dies, but is resurrected. The adjudicator should have died, but they loved putting her in this film as much as possible, she has plot armor as thick as any GoT character. 2 guys at the end give Wick 3 chances when they could have killed him, for Wick to kill them. Go walk until your almost dead into the desert, 'what a brilliant plan, no specific desert just a desert, that's sure to work!' And it does cause, 'reasons'(no reasons given). It's like the director thought "I wonder how much idiotic sh^t I can put in this movie for normies to enjoy it, and I can laugh at how stupid they are."

I'd probably explode with excitement. Then  I'd borrow the indomitable will of John Wick, reconstitute, and enjoy the bloodbath. Part 5 PLEASE! text: This one was a huge disappointment.  1.) Too much cheap looking CGI. Especially the knifes in that first bigger fight looked like something from a 90s movie. When he used the horse as a weapon wasn't much better and the motorcycle action scene was ruined by it too.  2.) The plot really jumped the shark with this weird world where everyone is an assassin, or working for assassins, or whatever.  Making it that unrealistic ruins everything. When it is such a unrealistic fantasy world, then the feats and achievements of the heroes start feeling unimpressive and boring and it becomes impossible to care about anything that happens. The first two were still somewhat believable, except that scene at the end of the second one, where suddenly everybody stops and stares at Wick. I hate it when directors ruthlessly flush everything down the drain just for the effect of one weird (they probably thought it was "cool") scene like that.  If in this weird other world everybody is somehow involved in the shadowy assassination business, then why were those Russian gangsters in the first movie the only ones not in on it and didn't know who they are dealing with? And how is there enough money in assassinating people to sustain such a enormous shadow economy, where somehow enough revenue is created to have assassins sit at every street corner, pretending to be bums 24/7? What well trained killer would do that for more than a day? Is that what they went to assassin school for? (Judging by the picture this movie paints of that world, every 3rd or so school must be a assassin school on that planet.)  3.) Halle Barry still doesn't work as an action hero. She looks as silly doing it as she looked in "Catwoman", just that now she's old on top of being tiny and having this lame "I'm such a serious and dangerous super killer!"-expression on her face while doing over-choreographed stunts that clearly don't look as if they would work without the cooperation of the bad guys. This NEVER works.  It was the same thing with Emilia Clarke in that "Terminator Genisys" movie. I don't know what it is, but those women can't sell it. You can almost see them count in their heads to get the right choreographed moment to come out of cover and shoot somebody. Every time they cram one of those actresses into such action roles, it looks like "Dancing with the Stars", with guns/swords.  Even the dogs are silly and dumb in that Casablanca action scene. The dogs always keep biting dead henchmen and apparently don't know when to stop, then the camera cuts away from them and suddenly they jump another dude and then keep biting and pulling that guy around after he is already dead. At what point does the dog figure out that it might be time to stop biting the dead guy and go for a new one and why is it always conveniently off screen?  It makes me angry that Reeves invested all that training and rehearsing and then it is turned to garbage in post production.
